00:14:57.850 --> 00:14:59.870
depending on which
potential you choose.

00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:04.000
So that's really--
this is the reason why

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.460
we need these more
accurate-- a way, at least,

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:07.900
to get more accurate potentials.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.210
And then you can get these
other properties, as I said.

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:14.100
So you can get things like
where the electrons are.

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:17.940
You can model things like
Raman spectra, which have

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:20.700
to do with electrons and light.

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:24.570
You can model things
like reactions.

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:29.310
Now, sometimes potentials--
like especially reacs.

00:15:29.310 --> 00:15:31.560
Did you run reacs potentials?

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:37.360
Reacs-- the name "reacs"
makes me think reaction.

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:38.570
Does it make you think that?

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:41.170
So they're actually
modeled for reactions.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:42.950
And that means that
they can break bonds.

00:15:42.950 --> 00:15:45.735
However, there are
plenty of reactions--

00:15:45.735 --> 00:15:47.640
AUDIENCE: [SNEEZES]

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:50.700
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: --salute--
where reacs can actually not

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:56.970
get the right physics, the right
structure of the potential.

00:15:56.970 --> 00:15:57.690
Why?

00:15:57.690 --> 00:15:59.340
Well, take a look at this one.

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:03.760
This is butadiene plus
ethylene going to cyclohexane--

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:04.260
hexene.

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:07.890
It's one of the simplest ways
you can actually make a ring.

00:16:07.890 --> 00:16:08.970
Watch those electrons.

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:14.860
Those are the electrons of
the part of the system that's

00:16:14.860 --> 00:16:15.860
doing the reaction.

00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:17.260
That's where the electrons are.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.280
And where those electrons are
is what determines everything

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:27.107
about the reaction-- the
barrier, whether it happens.

00:16:27.107 --> 00:16:28.690
And let's see if I
can get it to play.

00:16:28.690 --> 00:16:29.920
And now, watch them.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:30.430
Watch them.

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:31.840
It's like balloon animals.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:35.770
See, they pop up on the top,
and then they flow across.

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:37.540
And then they do
a big shape-shift

00:16:37.540 --> 00:16:40.110
as the reaction
actually happens,

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:45.250
and they curve back around,
and they bubble up on top.

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:49.030
And that's the final position
probability of those electrons.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:51.730
It's a very simple
reaction, but the behavior

00:16:51.730 --> 00:16:54.730
is extremely complex.

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:59.130
So when you fit a potential,
this is what you're ignoring.

00:16:59.130 --> 00:17:01.860
All of that complexity.

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:04.050
And you're trying to fit
it to some functional form,

00:17:04.050 --> 00:17:06.700
and reacs has a whole lot
of degrees of freedom,

00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:09.329
so it actually can fit some
of this complexity very well.

00:17:09.329 --> 00:17:12.930
But that just gives you a
sense of the kind of thing

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:17.640
that's happening, and why you
can miss important aspects

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:19.670
with potentials.

