00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:17.233
the infamous double
slit experiment.

00:35:17.233 --> 00:35:19.400
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Got to
know about the double slit.

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:21.140
- To understand this
experiment, we first

00:35:21.140 --> 00:35:27.020
need to see how particles, or
little balls of matter, act.

00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:29.890
If we randomly shoot
a small object--

00:35:29.890 --> 00:35:33.260
say, a marble--
at the screen, we

00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:35.780
see a pattern on the
back wall where they

00:35:35.780 --> 00:35:38.630
went through the slit and hit.

00:35:38.630 --> 00:35:42.380
Now, if we add a
second slit, we would

00:35:42.380 --> 00:35:46.360
expect to see a second band
duplicated to the right.

00:35:49.050 --> 00:35:52.570
Now let's look at waves.

00:35:52.570 --> 00:35:56.330
The waves hit the
slit and radiate out,

00:35:56.330 --> 00:36:00.140
striking the back wall
with the most intensity

00:36:00.140 --> 00:36:03.560
directly in line with the slit.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:06.380
The line of brightness
on the back screen

00:36:06.380 --> 00:36:08.710
shows that intensity.

00:36:08.710 --> 00:36:12.180
This is similar to the
line the marbles make.

00:36:12.180 --> 00:36:19.560
But when we add the second slit,
something different happens.

00:36:19.560 --> 00:36:24.750
If the top of one wave meets
the bottom of another wave,

00:36:24.750 --> 00:36:27.420
they cancel each other out.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:32.190
So now there is an interference
pattern on the back wall.

00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:36.570
Places where the two tops meet
are the highest intensity--

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:40.750
the bright lines-- and where
they cancel, there is nothing.

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:43.800
So when we throw things--

00:36:43.800 --> 00:36:48.690
that is, matter-- through
two slits, we get this--

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:52.560
two bands of [? hits. ?]
And with waves,

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:57.190
we get an interference
pattern of many bands.

00:36:57.190 --> 00:36:58.780
Good, so far.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:03.030
Now let's go quantum.

00:37:03.030 --> 00:37:06.820
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Now that's
what I'm talking about.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:11.950
- An electron is a tiny,
tiny bit of matter,

00:37:11.950 --> 00:37:14.310
like a tiny marble.

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:18.060
Let's fire a stream
through one slit.

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:20.190
It behaves just
like the marble--

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:22.850
a single band.

00:37:22.850 --> 00:37:27.380
So if we shoot these tiny
bits through two slits,

00:37:27.380 --> 00:37:32.320
we should get, like
the marbles, two bands.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:33.820
What?

00:37:33.820 --> 00:37:36.070
An interference pattern!

00:37:36.070 --> 00:37:40.480
We fired electrons, tiny
bits of matter through,

00:37:40.480 --> 00:37:45.430
and we get a pattern like
waves, not like little marbles.

00:37:45.430 --> 00:37:46.915
How?

00:37:46.915 --> 00:37:50.860
How could pieces of matter
create an interference pattern

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:52.570
like a wave?

00:37:52.570 --> 00:37:54.880
It doesn't make sense.

00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:57.580
But physicists are clever.

00:37:57.580 --> 00:38:00.370
They thought, maybe
those little balls

00:38:00.370 --> 00:38:04.120
are bouncing off each other
and creating that pattern.

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:08.140
So they decide to shoot
electrons through one

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:08.920
at a time.

00:38:08.920 --> 00:38:10.212
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: This is cool.

00:38:10.212 --> 00:38:13.920
- There is no way they can
interfere with each other.

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:17.370
But after an hour of this,
the same interference pattern

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:18.780
is seen to emerge.

00:38:18.780 --> 00:38:21.690
The conclusion is inescapable.

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:24.770
The single electron
leaves as a particle,

00:38:24.770 --> 00:38:28.740
becomes a wave of potentials,
goes through both slits,

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:33.650
and interferes with itself to
hit the wall like a particle.

00:38:33.650 --> 00:38:36.140
But mathematically,
it's even stranger.

00:38:36.140 --> 00:38:40.070
It goes through both slits,
and it goes through neither,

00:38:40.070 --> 00:38:42.140
and it goes through
just one, and it

00:38:42.140 --> 00:38:44.040
goes through just the other.

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:47.120
All of these possibilities
are in superposition

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:48.110
with each other.

00:38:48.110 --> 00:38:51.030
But physicists were
completely baffled by this,

00:38:51.030 --> 00:38:54.130
so they decided to
peek and see which

00:38:54.130 --> 00:38:57.770
slit it actually goes through.

00:38:57.770 --> 00:39:00.750
And they put a measuring
device by one slit

00:39:00.750 --> 00:39:03.960
to see which one it went
through and let it fly.

00:39:05.970 --> 00:39:09.300
But the quantum world
is far more mysterious

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:11.310
than they could have imagined.

00:39:11.310 --> 00:39:15.030
When they observed,
the electron went back

00:39:15.030 --> 00:39:17.040
to behaving like
a little marble!

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:21.510
It produced a pattern of two
bands, not an interference

00:39:21.510 --> 00:39:23.550
pattern of many.

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:28.740
The very act of
measuring, or observing,

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:31.680
which slit it went
through meant it only

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:35.180
went through one, not both.

00:39:35.180 --> 00:39:40.421
The electron decided
to act differently,

00:39:40.421 --> 00:39:43.820
as though it was aware
it was being watched.

00:39:45.350 --> 00:39:49.100
And it was here that
physicists stepped forever

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:53.510
into the strange neverworld
of quantum events.

00:39:53.510 --> 00:39:57.920
What is matter--
marbles or waves?

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:00.180
And waves of what?

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:05.575
And what does an observer
have to do with any of this?

00:40:05.575 --> 00:40:13.437
The observer collapsed the wave
function simply by observing.

