00:45:02.970 --> 00:45:04.410
about dead cats.

00:45:04.410 --> 00:45:07.100
And the final one to look into,
but I won't talk about more,

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:09.210
is called the EPR paradox.

00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:11.490
And this stands for Einstein,
Podolsky, and Rosen.

00:45:11.490 --> 00:45:14.270
And it's a very
interesting paradox, again,

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:16.020
that comes out of
quantum mechanics, which

00:45:16.020 --> 00:45:22.630
is that you can entangle
the states of two particles

00:45:22.630 --> 00:45:23.710
together--

00:45:23.710 --> 00:45:27.100
let's say the spin-- so
that its total is zero.

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:29.620
But one is one and
one is minus one.

00:45:29.620 --> 00:45:31.990
And now as you separate
them, because they

00:45:31.990 --> 00:45:34.750
were entangled at one
point, you can separate them

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:38.140
to very long distances, and
according to quantum mechanics,

00:45:38.140 --> 00:45:40.420
they both have to
really be both.

00:45:40.420 --> 00:45:44.110
One cannot be one and one minus
one-- the collection is zero.

00:45:44.110 --> 00:45:46.540
But one cannot be one and one
minus one until you measure

00:45:46.540 --> 00:45:47.040
one.

00:45:47.040 --> 00:45:49.180
And then that one is
something, and the other one

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:51.100
is the other something.

00:45:51.100 --> 00:45:53.740
And that actually leads to
some very interesting paradoxes

00:45:53.740 --> 00:45:56.290
involving information,
because you've

00:45:56.290 --> 00:45:58.570
gotten information about
something that's more

00:45:58.570 --> 00:46:01.480
than the speed of light away.

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:02.570
Is that possible?

00:46:02.570 --> 00:46:04.450
[INAUDIBLE]
wonderful discussions

00:46:04.450 --> 00:46:07.900
about this kind of stuff
that I won't go into.

00:46:07.900 --> 00:46:08.500
OK.

00:46:08.500 --> 00:46:11.470
So now we're going to get to--

00:46:11.470 --> 00:46:12.790
we're going to move--

00:46:12.790 --> 00:46:15.800
those are motivations.

00:46:15.800 --> 00:46:18.670
This is what everybody was
at the time grappling with,

00:46:18.670 --> 00:46:22.380
is how can we
explain these things?

00:46:22.380 --> 00:46:25.660
And what it really came
down to is that particles

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:27.760
can be both waves and--

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:31.080
everything can be both
waves and particles.

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:34.540
But especially when you get
down to very small masses,

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:38.760
the wave nature can dominate.

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:41.610
And that is the
case for electrons.

00:46:41.610 --> 00:46:44.400
So for waves, they have
particle-like properties,

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:46.985
and for particles, they can
have wavelike properties.

00:46:46.985 --> 00:46:49.680
And that's really
the key observation.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:51.810
That's the
wave-particle duality.

00:46:51.810 --> 00:46:57.420
And as you saw in the video,
what that means is that--

00:46:57.420 --> 00:47:06.270
you see, a wave is a wave,
which means it can have both--

00:47:06.270 --> 00:47:08.130
it can have interference.

00:47:08.130 --> 00:47:11.400
As you saw, the electron,
they shoot it one at a time.

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:13.020
Not interfering with
another electron.

00:47:13.020 --> 00:47:14.900
It's literally
interfering with itself.

00:47:17.218 --> 00:47:18.760
And you can see that
you can actually

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:21.603
get interference patterns,
and that diffraction pattern

00:47:21.603 --> 00:47:23.770
that you see on the plate
in the two-slit experiment

00:47:23.770 --> 00:47:28.227
is a measurable wavelike
property of the electron.

00:47:28.227 --> 00:47:30.060
You know what I love
so much about that is--

00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:32.070
I don't know if you
caught it, but it's

00:47:32.070 --> 00:47:34.670
shot out as a particle.

00:47:34.670 --> 00:47:36.830
It's got to go through
the slits as a wave.

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:39.660
There's no other
way to explain it.

00:47:39.660 --> 00:47:42.560
If you don't observe it,
it goes through as a wave.

00:47:42.560 --> 00:47:44.000
But then in order to--

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.300
the original experiments were
done with a photographic plate

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.310
that can only be--

00:47:49.310 --> 00:47:52.698
the track can only be
made if it's a particle.

00:47:52.698 --> 00:47:54.740
The position of the electron
has to be a particle

00:47:54.740 --> 00:47:56.630
to make the dot on the plate.

00:47:56.630 --> 00:47:59.087
So it goes from particle
to wave to particle.

00:47:59.087 --> 00:48:01.170
And that's really the
nature of quantum mechanics.

00:48:01.170 --> 00:48:04.100
You have to be able to
describe particles as waves.

00:48:04.100 --> 00:48:06.710
And so we start seeing
effects like this,

00:48:06.710 --> 00:48:11.900
where you can get constructive
interference from a particle.

00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:13.820
That's really cool.

00:48:13.820 --> 00:48:16.700
And that's what we need
to be able to describe

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:20.220
to describe the quantum
world in a computer.

00:48:20.220 --> 00:48:20.850
That's real.

00:48:20.850 --> 00:48:23.290
That's a water
dropping to make waves.

00:48:23.290 --> 00:48:25.650
This is actually an electron.

00:48:25.650 --> 00:48:30.390
This is where an electron
sits on a surface.

00:48:30.390 --> 00:48:31.860
I think that's a quantum corral.

00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:37.860
And it's been measured
experimentally--

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:40.740
this is the experimental setup.

00:48:40.740 --> 00:48:42.410
It's been measured
experimentally

00:48:42.410 --> 00:48:44.610
for bigger things
than electrons.

00:48:44.610 --> 00:48:47.470
You think electrons
are really tiny.

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:49.500
Oh, Grossman only
cares about them

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:53.520
for his electronics and optics,
but I care about bigger things,

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:54.480
like fullerenes.

00:48:54.480 --> 00:48:58.590
Well, if you take fullerenes
and you shoot them

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:03.750
through two slits, you also
get a diffraction pattern.

00:49:03.750 --> 00:49:04.750
This is real stuff.

00:49:04.750 --> 00:49:07.830
It happens for
real bigger things.

00:49:07.830 --> 00:49:13.140
OK, but now, could I
go through two slits?

00:49:13.140 --> 00:49:14.070
Is that possible?

00:49:14.070 --> 00:49:18.270
Am I quantum mechanical?

00:49:18.270 --> 00:49:20.700
AUDIENCE: Are you
observing yourself?

00:49:20.700 --> 00:49:22.935
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: I am--

00:49:22.935 --> 00:49:23.435
I--

00:49:25.375 --> 00:49:27.660
I don't have a good
response to that question.

00:49:27.660 --> 00:49:31.440
But I am not observing
myself and no one else is.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:34.400
Am I quantum mechanical?

00:49:34.400 --> 00:49:35.360
Yeah.

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:38.562
Why don't I create diffraction
patterns wherever I go?

00:49:38.562 --> 00:49:39.394
AUDIENCE: Too big.

00:49:39.394 --> 00:49:40.680
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Too big?

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:41.675
Don't read ahead!

00:49:41.675 --> 00:49:42.930
Why am I too big?

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:49.510
So where does this stuff end?

00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:53.577
Are you always a wave, no
matter how big you are?

00:49:53.577 --> 00:49:55.285
And that's where we're
missing something.

00:49:55.285 --> 00:49:56.890
We're missing something
really important.

00:49:56.890 --> 00:49:58.060
The answer is, absolutely.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:01.990
I am a wave, and
I'm proud of it.

00:50:01.990 --> 00:50:06.140
My arm right now is a quantum
mechanical-- this is a wave.

00:50:06.140 --> 00:50:07.440
This is not a particle.

00:50:07.440 --> 00:50:09.460
If I throw this chalk--

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:12.850
that was fun-- that's
not a particle.

00:50:12.850 --> 00:50:15.250
That was a wave I just threw.

00:50:15.250 --> 00:50:18.100
It has a wave
associated with it.

00:50:18.100 --> 00:50:19.420
It is very wavelike.

00:50:19.420 --> 00:50:21.730
But if I throw chalk
through two slits,

00:50:21.730 --> 00:50:23.770
will I get a
diffraction pattern?

00:50:23.770 --> 00:50:25.130
No.

00:50:25.130 --> 00:50:28.020
And now we're going to see why.

00:50:28.020 --> 00:50:30.030
When is a particle like a wave?

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.220
Well, it always is--

00:50:32.220 --> 00:50:33.580
but to varying degrees.

00:50:33.580 --> 00:50:37.290
And that's where de Broglie
came in and generalized

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:41.190
what Einstein had been working
on, and others, and said, look,

00:50:41.190 --> 00:50:42.810
everything has a wave.

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:47.010
Everything is both a wave
and a particle-- everything.

00:50:47.010 --> 00:50:51.150
And he said, and
we can associate--

00:50:51.150 --> 00:50:55.530
we can calculate a
wavelength to these things.

00:50:55.530 --> 00:50:56.630
Here's the electron.

00:50:56.630 --> 00:51:01.710
The wavelength of the electron
is 10 to the minus 10th meters.

00:51:01.710 --> 00:51:06.990
Now, why is that a distance
that is making electrons really

00:51:06.990 --> 00:51:09.000
quantum mechanical?

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:14.310
Or why can't I describe them
classically at that distance?

00:51:14.310 --> 00:51:16.170
What's that distance?

00:51:16.170 --> 00:51:17.160
AUDIENCE: Angstrom?

00:51:17.160 --> 00:51:19.140
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
It's an angstrom.

00:51:19.140 --> 00:51:23.000
What happens at
the angstrom level?

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:24.140
Like, what's an angstrom?

00:51:24.140 --> 00:51:26.270
What's 4 angstroms?

00:51:26.270 --> 00:51:28.232
What's 2.447 angstroms?

00:51:28.232 --> 00:51:28.940
AUDIENCE: Carbon.

00:51:28.940 --> 00:51:30.430
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Carbon.

00:51:30.430 --> 00:51:31.510
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE] carbon.

00:51:34.490 --> 00:51:36.390
So that's the level of bonds.

00:51:36.390 --> 00:51:37.810
This is it, man.

00:51:37.810 --> 00:51:41.440
This is where--
that wavelength is

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:44.650
the same size as the
kind of distances

00:51:44.650 --> 00:51:47.440
that matter to an electron,
like the distance from one

00:51:47.440 --> 00:51:48.970
atom to another.

00:51:48.970 --> 00:51:50.240
It's the same.

00:51:50.240 --> 00:51:51.970
So that means--
because the wavelength

00:51:51.970 --> 00:51:57.110
is so similar to the
world of the electron,

00:51:57.110 --> 00:52:01.403
then that quantum effect is
going to be really important.

00:52:01.403 --> 00:52:04.640
And the wavelength
is 100 times smaller

00:52:04.640 --> 00:52:08.060
for a fullerene, which
means that it's maybe

00:52:08.060 --> 00:52:11.480
less important for things
we do with fullerenes.

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:14.300
What do we do with
fullerenes, by the way?

00:52:14.300 --> 00:52:17.930
Has anybody done
anything with fullerenes?

00:52:17.930 --> 00:52:20.513
Probably not, but what
could we do with fullerenes?

00:52:23.900 --> 00:52:24.770
No.

00:52:24.770 --> 00:52:26.150
We're still working on it.

00:52:26.150 --> 00:52:26.660
Make what?

00:52:26.660 --> 00:52:27.710
AUDIENCE: Make soccer balls.

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:29.002
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Soccer balls.

00:52:31.250 --> 00:52:33.920
You can make pretty high
temperature superconductors--

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:36.140
what would have been considered
very high temperature

00:52:36.140 --> 00:52:38.300
before high TC came on.

00:52:38.300 --> 00:52:40.370
You can also make solar cells.

00:52:40.370 --> 00:52:41.450
You can make electronics.

00:52:41.450 --> 00:52:44.535
You can make all kinds of
interesting chemistries.

00:52:44.535 --> 00:52:46.910
And most of the time, the
quantum mechanics won't matter,

00:52:46.910 --> 00:52:49.290
but that experiment showed
that you can still measure it.

00:52:49.290 --> 00:52:51.770
Now I have a
baseball, and here's

00:52:51.770 --> 00:52:54.080
the wavelength of a baseball.

00:52:54.080 --> 00:52:57.230
Can I measure that?

00:52:57.230 --> 00:53:00.250
But it has a wavelength.

00:53:00.250 --> 00:53:03.520
And it's just-- and
so do I. So do you.

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:05.860
It's just that this is
20 orders of magnitude

00:53:05.860 --> 00:53:09.780
smaller than the diameter
of the nucleus of an atom.

00:53:09.780 --> 00:53:12.810
That's how tiny the
wavelength is associated

00:53:12.810 --> 00:53:15.150
with these more larger objects.

00:53:15.150 --> 00:53:17.700
So you see, these are
very quantum mechanical,

00:53:17.700 --> 00:53:19.410
and they do have--

00:53:19.410 --> 00:53:23.140
they would be able to
give you the same effect,

00:53:23.140 --> 00:53:25.540
if you could pick up--

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:27.370
if you can measure
distances that small.

00:53:31.970 --> 00:53:38.710
So what we have in
classical versus quantum

00:53:38.710 --> 00:53:42.280
is that we have to
describe in a computer

00:53:42.280 --> 00:53:44.800
the mechanics of
waves, as opposed

00:53:44.800 --> 00:53:46.340
to the mechanics of particles.

00:53:46.340 --> 00:53:47.343
So what we had before--

00:53:47.343 --> 00:53:48.760
OK, so that way,
we're going to be

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:52.300
able to describe the wave
and the particle behavior.

00:53:52.300 --> 00:53:55.470
What we had before was this.

00:53:55.470 --> 00:53:57.310
This is the mechanics
of a particle,

00:53:57.310 --> 00:54:00.130
and you all did a lot
of simulating of this.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:04.410
Did you guys do--

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:07.890
so did you do
molecular dynamics?

00:54:07.890 --> 00:54:08.420
Yeah.

00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:10.010
So you know about that.

00:54:10.010 --> 00:54:14.160
And you did that with velocity
