AUDIENCE: Got it from there.

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:47.050
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah.

00:54:47.050 --> 00:54:48.240
And so they're-- right.

00:54:48.240 --> 00:54:49.460
So here's the thing.

00:54:49.460 --> 00:54:52.630
There are many ways to
solve this equation.

00:54:52.630 --> 00:54:57.910
And some are more efficient to
put on a computer than others.

00:54:57.910 --> 00:55:01.190
But none of them are
really very complicated.

00:55:01.190 --> 00:55:03.640
We're going to have the same
thing with quantum mechanics,

00:55:03.640 --> 00:55:05.265
it just gets a little
more complicated,

00:55:05.265 --> 00:55:07.385
because the equation
is more complicated.

00:55:07.385 --> 00:55:09.010
But we're going to
have the same thing.

00:55:09.010 --> 00:55:10.630
We'll have an equation
for quantum mechanics,

00:55:10.630 --> 00:55:12.213
and there'll be many
ways to solve it.

00:55:12.213 --> 00:55:15.400
And we're going to learn
a little bit about them,

00:55:15.400 --> 00:55:17.302
and then just kind of
move on and apply it.

00:55:17.302 --> 00:55:19.510
But we'll learn a little
bit about the different ways

00:55:19.510 --> 00:55:21.830
to solve it.

00:55:21.830 --> 00:55:26.130
So this wave is now-- you see,
instead of being a particle,

00:55:26.130 --> 00:55:27.540
it's now an expectation.

00:55:27.540 --> 00:55:28.430
It's a vibration.

00:55:28.430 --> 00:55:30.600
So what we need to
know about a wave--

00:55:30.600 --> 00:55:33.780
oh, yeah, psi.

00:55:33.780 --> 00:55:35.040
Psi.

00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:38.870
When you see psi, that's like
quantum mechanics, right?

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:39.870
Or a fraternity?

00:55:39.870 --> 00:55:41.830
I don't know.

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:43.710
But anyway, here it's
quantum mechanics.

00:55:43.710 --> 00:55:45.720
And psi is the function.

00:55:45.720 --> 00:55:46.238
That's it.

00:55:46.238 --> 00:55:47.405
That's what we want to know.

00:55:47.405 --> 00:55:50.520
That's the wave function.

00:55:50.520 --> 00:55:55.240
That's what we're solving for
for the next so many weeks--

00:55:55.240 --> 00:55:56.020
five weeks?

00:55:56.020 --> 00:55:58.632
Six weeks.

00:55:58.632 --> 00:56:00.090
We're going to be
solving for this.

00:56:00.090 --> 00:56:01.230
This is the wave function.

00:56:01.230 --> 00:56:05.490
This is what tells us where
those electrons are going to be

00:56:05.490 --> 00:56:07.270
and how they're going to behave.

00:56:07.270 --> 00:56:09.360
And so the simplest way
to write down a wave

00:56:09.360 --> 00:56:12.270
is what's called the plane
wave, which is just a cosine--

00:56:12.270 --> 00:56:16.560
it's a cosine plus sine,
where you have an amplitude,

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:22.980
and then you have this vector
k at the spatial position,

00:56:22.980 --> 00:56:25.947
and then this frequency
times the time.

00:56:25.947 --> 00:56:27.780
So this is the simplest
way to write a wave,

00:56:27.780 --> 00:56:29.790
and you can find
little nice animations

00:56:29.790 --> 00:56:34.430
on Wikipedia of what a wave
like that would look like.

00:56:34.430 --> 00:56:36.740
That's a plane wave.

00:56:36.740 --> 00:56:39.350
And you can see that it's
called a plane wave because you

00:56:39.350 --> 00:56:43.220
can look at it as these
moving planes of some sort

00:56:43.220 --> 00:56:45.770
of constant magnitude.

00:56:45.770 --> 00:56:49.842
It's a very simple way
of describing this.

00:56:49.842 --> 00:56:51.340
Maybe there are
more complex ways,

00:56:51.340 --> 00:56:55.300
but this is going to be one
that we like in this class.

00:56:55.300 --> 00:56:58.280
Now, what I was telling
you about before is

00:56:58.280 --> 00:57:00.320
what de Broglie did,
which he said, look,

00:57:00.320 --> 00:57:04.490
everything can be
described as a wave.

00:57:04.490 --> 00:57:06.830
Everything can
have a wavelength.

00:57:06.830 --> 00:57:09.920
And the wavelength
associated with anything

00:57:09.920 --> 00:57:11.840
is going to look like this.

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:12.590
Did I put it here?

00:57:12.590 --> 00:57:13.220
Yeah.

00:57:13.220 --> 00:57:17.390
It's going to go as h
divided by the momentum--

00:57:17.390 --> 00:57:21.190
the mass times the velocity.

00:57:21.190 --> 00:57:22.660
So there is a
wavelength that can

00:57:22.660 --> 00:57:25.360
be associated with anything.

00:57:25.360 --> 00:57:26.890
That's what de Broglie said.

00:57:26.890 --> 00:57:30.880
So he generalized what
Einstein had been working on

00:57:30.880 --> 00:57:34.630
with light to say that
this would be something

00:57:34.630 --> 00:57:35.590
that anything can have.

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:39.550
It can have a
description that can be

00:57:39.550 --> 00:57:43.340
described by a wave function.

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:45.890
And that's what Einstein
already did this.

00:57:45.890 --> 00:57:46.640
He did that part.

00:57:46.640 --> 00:57:49.160
He said the energy
of that wave would be

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:50.750
proportional to its frequency.

00:57:50.750 --> 00:57:53.610
That was part of the
photoelectric effect.

00:57:53.610 --> 00:57:55.560
OK, so how do we describe it?

00:57:55.560 --> 00:58:01.140
So in the last 10, 15 minutes,
we'll say, this is it.

00:58:01.140 --> 00:58:03.300
This is where we've
been building to,

00:58:03.300 --> 00:58:05.070
because we're going
to end with what

00:58:05.070 --> 00:58:08.070
we need to do in this class,
which is solve an equation.

00:58:08.070 --> 00:58:10.500
We're going to end just
with a little bit of feeling

00:58:10.500 --> 00:58:13.080
of our F equals ma.

00:58:13.080 --> 00:58:16.260
And our F equals ma is
the Schrodinger equation.

00:58:16.260 --> 00:58:20.970
And I won't talk about
how it was derived.

00:58:23.680 --> 00:58:25.890
It's actually-- it's
a wonderful story.

00:58:25.890 --> 00:58:28.780
He was very frustrated,
because this didn't actually

00:58:28.780 --> 00:58:30.340
agree with some of
the work that was

00:58:30.340 --> 00:58:33.860
being done on relativistic
effects solving this equation.

00:58:33.860 --> 00:58:36.710
And so he refused to
publish, actually,

00:58:36.710 --> 00:58:38.590
his equation for quite a time.

00:58:38.590 --> 00:58:41.170
And he took a
retreat to his cabin,

00:58:41.170 --> 00:58:45.880
and apparently came back and
decided he would publish.

00:58:45.880 --> 00:58:48.340
I love reading these stories.

00:58:48.340 --> 00:58:49.210
Those were the days.

00:58:49.210 --> 00:58:51.070
People really published
when they really

00:58:51.070 --> 00:58:53.770
had something important to say.

00:58:53.770 --> 00:58:56.560
That's cool.

00:58:56.560 --> 00:58:57.940
And that was-- it
was just really

00:58:57.940 --> 00:59:00.460
neat to watch the communication
between Schrodinger

00:59:00.460 --> 00:59:06.550
and Einstein, and all these just
brilliant people of the time.

00:59:06.550 --> 00:59:07.450
This is our equation.

00:59:07.450 --> 00:59:10.708
This is a wave equation.

00:59:10.708 --> 00:59:12.850
This tells us what
we need to know.

00:59:12.850 --> 00:59:18.220
This tells us how this function
evolved in time and space.

00:59:18.220 --> 00:59:26.230
And the key here is that this
side here has the terms--

00:59:26.230 --> 00:59:31.240
this has the momentum
squared term, which-- you

00:59:31.240 --> 00:59:33.040
can look at the previous page.

00:59:33.040 --> 00:59:37.460
When you look at de
Broglie and Einstein,

00:59:37.460 --> 00:59:41.890
h bar omega is the energy
from the frequency,

00:59:41.890 --> 00:59:43.660
and then the
momentum, then you can

00:59:43.660 --> 00:59:47.590
go back and see why these
things make a lot of sense.

00:59:47.590 --> 00:59:50.470
But this is going to be--

00:59:50.470 --> 00:59:53.350
this second derivative
here, spatial derivative,

00:59:53.350 --> 00:59:56.420
is going to give you
the momentum squared.

00:59:56.420 --> 00:59:59.360
So that looks kind of like
a kinetic energy term.

00:59:59.360 --> 01:00:03.020
And that's the kinetic energy
plus the potential energy

01:00:03.020 --> 01:00:07.400
times the wave
function gives you

01:00:07.400 --> 01:00:11.060
something that's equal to the
time dependence of that wave

01:00:11.060 --> 01:00:11.885
function.

01:00:11.885 --> 01:00:14.120
The time derivative
of the wave function.

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:15.770
That's the Schrodinger equation.

01:00:15.770 --> 01:00:24.650
And for this class, we will
consider that left-hand part

01:00:24.650 --> 01:00:30.340
that has the parts that give
you the potential energy

01:00:30.340 --> 01:00:31.390
and the kinetic energy.

01:00:31.390 --> 01:00:35.660
That's basically how you can
think of this, of the particle.

01:00:35.660 --> 01:00:38.600
But oh, that's the kinetic
energy of the particle,

01:00:38.600 --> 01:00:41.520
but for a wave.

01:00:41.520 --> 01:00:43.200
And again, you can
see why, because you

01:00:43.200 --> 01:00:45.660
can go back and see
what this gives you,

01:00:45.660 --> 01:00:48.150
what k this gives you.

01:00:48.150 --> 01:00:54.150
So that's the kinetic energy,
but it's meant for a wave.

01:00:54.150 --> 01:00:57.360
And if we assume that this
energy part doesn't depend

01:00:57.360 --> 01:00:58.950
on time, then the
Schrodinger equation

01:00:58.950 --> 01:01:01.200
is much easier to solve,
and we get something

01:01:01.200 --> 01:01:02.300
that's time-independent.

01:01:02.300 --> 01:01:03.925
And that's what we'll
do in this class,

01:01:03.925 --> 01:01:07.130
because we can separate it into
a spatial part and a time part,

01:01:07.130 --> 01:01:08.880
and then we can just
ignore the time part,

01:01:08.880 --> 01:01:12.780
and we can call both
sides equal to a constant.

01:01:12.780 --> 01:01:15.460
This is just some
very simple algebra.

01:01:15.460 --> 01:01:17.340
And if we do that, we
can set them both equal

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:20.220
to some constant, let's
call it E, which is--

01:01:20.220 --> 01:01:22.120
there's a reason for that.

01:01:22.120 --> 01:01:24.330
And then this full
psi with the time

01:01:24.330 --> 01:01:27.240
will depend on the spatial
part times this exponential,

01:01:27.240 --> 01:01:29.162
and we'll just ignore
this for this class.

01:01:29.162 --> 01:01:30.870
We're just going to
care about this part.

01:01:34.440 --> 01:01:36.030
OK.

01:01:36.030 --> 01:01:38.625
So let's end with-- there's
these couple of examples

01:01:38.625 --> 01:01:39.750
that some of you have seen.

01:01:39.750 --> 01:01:41.750
How many of you have not
seen particle in a box?

01:01:44.390 --> 01:01:45.300
Couple people.

01:01:45.300 --> 01:01:46.320
OK.

01:01:46.320 --> 01:01:47.790
But if you have
seen it, you know

01:01:47.790 --> 01:01:50.580
this is still going to be
fun, because particle in a box

01:01:50.580 --> 01:01:52.510
is always fun.

01:01:52.510 --> 01:01:58.230
So all particle in a box
is it's the spatial part

01:01:58.230 --> 01:02:04.500
of the Schrodinger equation
solved for one of the simplest

01:02:04.500 --> 01:02:06.480
systems you can
imagine, which is

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:10.780
that you have some quantum
mechanical particle that can

01:02:10.780 --> 01:02:13.690
exist inside of this region.

01:02:13.690 --> 01:02:16.400
And so in this region,
there's no potential energy.

01:02:16.400 --> 01:02:18.880
It's just a free particle.

01:02:18.880 --> 01:02:21.100
It's a free wave.

01:02:21.100 --> 01:02:25.060
But then it has these
boundaries that go to infinity.

01:02:25.060 --> 01:02:26.650
And because it has
a potential that's

01:02:26.650 --> 01:02:30.300
infinite at the
boundaries there's

01:02:30.300 --> 01:02:34.540
only one solution here, which
is that the function has

01:02:34.540 --> 01:02:36.160
to be zero.

01:02:36.160 --> 01:02:40.790
And you can convince yourself
of that just by looking at this.

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:44.432
If this is infinity,
psi has to be zero.

01:02:44.432 --> 01:02:45.390
It's the only solution.

01:02:48.210 --> 01:02:50.910
So here's what becomes really
interesting about this.

01:02:50.910 --> 01:02:54.160
So you have-- if you look at
this equation, and you say,

01:02:54.160 --> 01:02:56.820
well, OK, outside--

01:02:56.820 --> 01:02:59.100
so you have two equations
you can write-- one

01:02:59.100 --> 01:03:00.960
where there's a V,
but it's infinite,

01:03:00.960 --> 01:03:04.380
in this case, and one where
V is zero, in which case

01:03:04.380 --> 01:03:07.150
that part drops out, and this
is the equation you're solving.

01:03:07.150 --> 01:03:10.010
And this has a general
solution, which looks like this.

01:03:10.010 --> 01:03:13.570
It's a sine plus a cosine.

01:03:13.570 --> 01:03:16.120
And from this
general solution, you

01:03:16.120 --> 01:03:19.030
can actually write
down what E is.

01:03:19.030 --> 01:03:22.810
That's actually very fairly
simple algebra to get to that.

01:03:22.810 --> 01:03:26.350
But what becomes really
interesting and exciting

01:03:26.350 --> 01:03:28.340
is when you apply the
boundary conditions.

01:03:28.340 --> 01:03:30.970
So when you look at
what has to happen here,

01:03:30.970 --> 01:03:33.760
you have constraints.

01:03:33.760 --> 01:03:37.010
And those constraints lead
to something really important

01:03:37.010 --> 01:03:40.520
that was really, really
frustrating all these people.

01:03:40.520 --> 01:03:42.212
What is it?

01:03:42.212 --> 01:03:43.170
AUDIENCE: Quantization.

01:03:43.170 --> 01:03:44.940
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
Leads to quantization.

01:03:44.940 --> 01:03:45.810
That's it.

01:03:45.810 --> 01:03:47.130
That's the ticket.

01:03:47.130 --> 01:03:51.630
It's when you put boundary
conditions on the simplest

01:03:51.630 --> 01:03:57.170
quantum particle, quantum thing
imaginable, a thing in a box,

01:03:57.170 --> 01:03:59.150
you quantize it.

01:03:59.150 --> 01:04:01.550
You quantize it
because, you see,

01:04:01.550 --> 01:04:03.800
when I put these
boundary conditions on,

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:08.630
I'm saying that there are
only certain allowable values

01:04:08.630 --> 01:04:13.520
for this, because of this.

01:04:18.130 --> 01:04:20.440
So the boundary conditions
cause quantization,

01:04:20.440 --> 01:04:23.110
and that's what gives
rise to the whole thing.

01:04:23.110 --> 01:04:29.230
That's what gives rise to this
whole world of energy levels,

01:04:29.230 --> 01:04:30.940
and a lot of the
things that we talked

01:04:30.940 --> 01:04:35.870
about in the beginning that were
so challenging to understand.

01:04:35.870 --> 01:04:36.950
So you have quantization.

01:04:36.950 --> 01:04:38.117
You also have normalization.

01:04:38.117 --> 01:04:41.120
We're not going to go
through this in great detail,

01:04:41.120 --> 01:04:45.560
but that also helps you
understand what A is.

01:04:45.560 --> 01:04:47.825
But you see there,
that has to be.

01:04:47.825 --> 01:04:52.820
k can only be n pi over L
where n is some integer.

01:04:52.820 --> 01:04:56.360
It can only be that because
of those boundaries.

01:04:56.360 --> 01:04:59.630
And if you go back to the
previous page, you can see why.

01:04:59.630 --> 01:05:03.320
So now, your energy, which
was nice and general as k,

01:05:03.320 --> 01:05:06.500
going as k squared, can
only go as n squared

01:05:06.500 --> 01:05:07.650
h bar squared pi squared.

01:05:07.650 --> 01:05:11.360
So it can only go
at certain values.

01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:12.710
It cannot be anything else.

01:05:15.900 --> 01:05:18.480
And what you get, then,
is you get energies.

01:05:18.480 --> 01:05:22.830
So you get energies that
have very discrete values.

01:05:22.830 --> 01:05:25.050
And that starts to
remind me of what?

01:05:25.050 --> 01:05:27.722
What experiment?

01:05:27.722 --> 01:05:28.722
AUDIENCE: Photoelectric?

01:05:28.722 --> 01:05:30.055
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Photoelectric?

01:05:30.055 --> 01:05:31.430
OK.

01:05:31.430 --> 01:05:34.902
And what else, where you
only saw discrete values?

01:05:34.902 --> 01:05:35.860
AUDIENCE: The spectrum?

01:05:35.860 --> 01:05:37.760
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: The spectra.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:38.960
The lines.

01:05:38.960 --> 01:05:40.992
You only saw discrete colors.

01:05:40.992 --> 01:05:42.200
You only see discrete colors.

01:05:42.200 --> 01:05:45.350
You guys can take a
telescope and look,

01:05:45.350 --> 01:05:46.880
and you'll only see
discrete colors.

01:05:46.880 --> 01:05:48.950
Now, it also gives
you something else.

01:05:48.950 --> 01:05:52.970
It gives you psi, which
gives you these curves.

01:05:52.970 --> 01:05:58.620
So you see, for the first
solution, n equals 1,

01:05:58.620 --> 01:06:00.580
you get a psi that
looks like that.

01:06:00.580 --> 01:06:02.760
But for the next
allowed value, you

01:06:02.760 --> 01:06:04.200
get a different shape for psi.

01:06:04.200 --> 01:06:05.790
And for the next
allowed value, you

01:06:05.790 --> 01:06:08.840
get yet another shape for psi.

01:06:08.840 --> 01:06:11.060
Oh, boy, is this important.

01:06:11.060 --> 01:06:12.170
Seriously.

01:06:12.170 --> 01:06:13.430
Check this out, OK?

01:06:13.430 --> 01:06:16.310
Because now-- OK, so
that helps explain this.

01:06:16.310 --> 01:06:18.140
It looks like it might.

01:06:18.140 --> 01:06:24.200
And now we're going to do it
for V equals something that

01:06:24.200 --> 01:06:27.710
looks more like a
harmonic potential,

01:06:27.710 --> 01:06:31.710
and we're going to get
equations that look like this.

01:06:31.710 --> 01:06:32.210
You see?

01:06:32.210 --> 01:06:33.710
We get energy levels--

01:06:33.710 --> 01:06:35.930
the quantized energy
levels that look like this,

01:06:35.930 --> 01:06:38.217
and we get psis
that look like this.

01:06:38.217 --> 01:06:40.550
And these are psi squareds,
which I'll tell you about in

01:06:40.550 --> 01:06:42.680
a minute.

01:06:42.680 --> 01:06:46.190
And that starts to
look a whole lot--

01:06:46.190 --> 01:06:47.150
do I have it?

01:06:47.150 --> 01:06:52.880
That starts to look a whole
lot like the hydrogen atom.

01:06:52.880 --> 01:06:55.880
You see, look at these psis.

01:06:55.880 --> 01:06:58.840
Look at the shapes of those.

01:06:58.840 --> 01:07:01.080
Those have structure,
and they also have zeros.

01:07:01.080 --> 01:07:03.770
They have places
where they go to zero.

01:07:03.770 --> 01:07:05.900
Now, here's the critical thing.

01:07:05.900 --> 01:07:11.850
The shape of the psi
squared is the answer.

01:07:11.850 --> 01:07:15.090
It's where the electron
is going to be.

01:07:15.090 --> 01:07:20.800
It is the probability of finding
the electron anywhere in space.

01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:22.630
Psi squared is the
probability of finding

01:07:22.630 --> 01:07:26.310
a quantum mechanical
particle anywhere in space.

01:07:26.310 --> 01:07:28.930
It is the wave
function, and it is also

01:07:28.930 --> 01:07:31.720
where the particle will be
with a given probability.

01:07:31.720 --> 01:07:36.640
So the probability of finding
this particle in a harmonic

01:07:36.640 --> 01:07:39.490
well is going to
be largest here,

01:07:39.490 --> 01:07:41.980
and then almost zero there.

01:07:41.980 --> 01:07:45.740
And then it's going to
go up again, further out.

01:07:45.740 --> 01:07:47.410
And you have these
different solutions

01:07:47.410 --> 01:07:51.100
that only happen for
certain energies.

01:07:51.100 --> 01:07:53.860
That is exactly what's observed.

01:07:53.860 --> 01:07:57.220
So the psi squared
is the probability

01:07:57.220 --> 01:07:58.270
you find a particle.

01:08:01.370 --> 01:08:04.310
Psi, we don't know what it is.

01:08:04.310 --> 01:08:06.280
We don't know what psi is.

01:08:06.280 --> 01:08:07.910
Does anybody know what psi is?

01:08:07.910 --> 01:08:09.200
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:09.200 --> 01:08:12.782
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: No,
that's psi squared.

01:08:12.782 --> 01:08:14.990
Psi is what we solve for in
the Schrodinger equation,

01:08:14.990 --> 01:08:17.073
and that's we're going to
solve for in this class.

01:08:17.073 --> 01:08:19.220
Psi squared gives
us the probability

01:08:19.220 --> 01:08:21.260
of finding that particle.

01:08:21.260 --> 01:08:21.979
What is psi?

01:08:30.170 --> 01:08:30.920
What does it mean?

01:08:33.750 --> 01:08:34.274
Any guesses?

01:08:38.439 --> 01:08:40.899
The square of it
is the probability

01:08:40.899 --> 01:08:43.279
that you can find a
particle anywhere.

01:08:43.279 --> 01:08:46.270
But what is psi itself?

01:08:46.270 --> 01:08:50.890
People have struggled
with this a lot.

01:08:50.890 --> 01:08:52.120
And you know what I think?

01:08:52.120 --> 01:08:54.220
I think people have given up.

01:08:54.220 --> 01:08:56.140
Because when you
read old textbooks,

01:08:56.140 --> 01:08:57.260
old quantum textbooks--

01:08:57.260 --> 01:09:00.189
I'm talking from
the '30s and '40s,

01:09:00.189 --> 01:09:01.880
they talk about
that a whole lot.

01:09:01.880 --> 01:09:03.640
And when you read new
quantum textbooks,

01:09:03.640 --> 01:09:06.359
they don't talk
about it anymore.

01:09:06.359 --> 01:09:08.040
Because we just
don't really know,

01:09:08.040 --> 01:09:11.160
is the answer, what is the
physical meaning of psi.

01:09:11.160 --> 01:09:13.520
Isn't that so cool?

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:17.297
We don't really have
a good grip on it.

01:09:17.297 --> 01:09:18.880
There's a lot of
different discussions

01:09:18.880 --> 01:09:20.529
around what it could be.

01:09:20.529 --> 01:09:22.279
But this is the thing
that means something

01:09:22.279 --> 01:09:23.810
we can measure directly.

01:09:23.810 --> 01:09:27.590
It's the distribution of
where that particle is.

01:09:27.590 --> 01:09:29.569
You see, so this is it.

01:09:29.569 --> 01:09:31.250
This is an electron around--

01:09:31.250 --> 01:09:34.790
this is the electron of
hydrogen. And you see,

01:09:34.790 --> 01:09:38.150
when that electron is in--
let's take a look at this.

01:09:38.150 --> 01:09:40.609
This is really important.

01:09:43.540 --> 01:09:46.990
When that electron
is in this shell,

01:09:46.990 --> 01:09:50.395
we already know
that's called the 1s.

01:09:50.395 --> 01:09:53.670
The psi for that
first allowed energy

01:09:53.670 --> 01:09:58.090
level, that first allowed
energy level has a shape to it,

01:09:58.090 --> 01:10:00.290
and it's spherical,
and it looks like that.

01:10:00.290 --> 01:10:04.420
And therefore, that is the
probability distribution

01:10:04.420 --> 01:10:05.120
of the electron.

01:10:05.120 --> 01:10:06.790
That's where it can be in space.

01:10:09.805 --> 01:10:16.550
If I measure where that electron
is, where's it going to be?

01:10:23.140 --> 01:10:24.430
Yeah.

01:10:24.430 --> 01:10:26.260
AUDIENCE: I mean,
if you measure it,

01:10:26.260 --> 01:10:28.720
you're going to get back
some position for it,

01:10:28.720 --> 01:10:30.850
and it's going to
be at that position.

01:10:30.850 --> 01:10:32.410
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
And I love that.

01:10:32.410 --> 01:10:35.080
If I measure it, it will
be where I measure it.

01:10:35.080 --> 01:10:35.878
Which is true.

01:10:35.878 --> 01:10:37.420
And that's actually
the right answer.

01:10:37.420 --> 01:10:40.120
But where will it be
according to that picture?

01:10:40.120 --> 01:10:43.300
How can I use this picture to
tell me where it's going to be?

01:10:48.750 --> 01:10:52.820
That is psi squared for
the electron of hydrogen

01:10:52.820 --> 01:10:53.690
in the first level.

01:10:59.040 --> 01:10:59.540
Yeah.

01:10:59.633 --> 01:11:01.050
AUDIENCE: You guess
as to where it

01:11:01.050 --> 01:11:04.252
will be within that boundary.

01:11:04.252 --> 01:11:05.210
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah.

01:11:05.210 --> 01:11:09.200
I mean, basically, the
answer is that it tells me

01:11:09.200 --> 01:11:12.800
where it is more or
less likely to be,

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:14.830
but it doesn't tell
me where it will be.

01:11:14.830 --> 01:11:17.040
It can't tell me that.

01:11:17.040 --> 01:11:19.170
Psi squared only tells
me a probability.

01:11:19.170 --> 01:11:21.000
It only tells me--

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:22.620
it can tell me where
it can never be.

01:11:25.413 --> 01:11:26.330
That's what these are.

01:11:26.330 --> 01:11:27.620
Those are those zeros.

01:11:27.620 --> 01:11:31.790
When psi squared is zero, that
electron can never be there.

01:11:31.790 --> 01:11:35.390
But it also can tell me
with more likelihood or less

01:11:35.390 --> 01:11:36.990
where I might find it.

01:11:36.990 --> 01:11:39.390
So if I measure it 10 times,
well, most of the time,

01:11:39.390 --> 01:11:40.265
I'll find it in here.

01:11:40.265 --> 01:11:43.960
Maybe once I find
it kind of out here.

01:11:43.960 --> 01:11:45.850
That's the nature of
quantum mechanics.

01:11:45.850 --> 01:11:48.400
That's the relationship between
the psi that we're going

01:11:48.400 --> 01:11:54.860
to solve for and the real deal.

01:11:54.860 --> 01:11:58.490
Now, what you find, then,
is see, the 1s is here,

01:11:58.490 --> 01:11:59.820
and then the 2s is here.

01:11:59.820 --> 01:12:05.080
So these are those
allowable energy levels

01:12:05.080 --> 01:12:07.780
for the atom, which we'll
start with that next time.

01:12:07.780 --> 01:12:11.350
But-- wait, don't go,
we're not done yet.

01:12:11.350 --> 01:12:16.500
So now, I've said that
the system is quantized,

01:12:16.500 --> 01:12:20.100
which means it can only
have certain energies.

01:12:20.100 --> 01:12:24.000
That's what the
boundary conditions do.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:27.090
How does that solve my
classical atom problem?

01:12:27.090 --> 01:12:30.662
The atom only living for 10
to the minus 12th seconds.

01:12:30.662 --> 01:12:31.620
How does it solve that?

01:12:43.800 --> 01:12:48.540
So basically-- yeah.

01:12:48.540 --> 01:12:51.610
AUDIENCE: It can't radiate away
just a little bit of energy.

01:12:51.610 --> 01:12:55.222
It can't fall in
just a little bit.

01:12:55.222 --> 01:12:56.680
If it's going to
radiate energy, it

01:12:56.680 --> 01:12:58.270
has to fall down
an entire level.

01:12:58.270 --> 01:12:58.840
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Exactly.

01:12:58.840 --> 01:12:59.350
Yeah.

01:12:59.350 --> 01:13:00.910
That's exactly right.

01:13:00.910 --> 01:13:05.530
These electrons-- it
solves the problem

01:13:05.530 --> 01:13:08.140
of the electron
collapsing into the core

01:13:08.140 --> 01:13:10.540
because it says the electron
no longer can collapse

01:13:10.540 --> 01:13:13.090
into the core, basically.

01:13:13.090 --> 01:13:15.340
We've quantized it, so
it just can't do that.

01:13:15.340 --> 01:13:18.400
Because you see, here's the 2s.

01:13:18.400 --> 01:13:20.470
And then the 2p--

01:13:20.470 --> 01:13:22.270
you see, there's
s, and there's 2s,

01:13:22.270 --> 01:13:25.160
and then the 2p has
some shape to it.

01:13:25.160 --> 01:13:26.440
I'm just going to put wiggles.

01:13:26.440 --> 01:13:28.040
It's not just a sphere anymore.

01:13:28.040 --> 01:13:29.920
It's got shape.

01:13:29.920 --> 01:13:32.020
When you go up higher
in energy, that psi

01:13:32.020 --> 01:13:34.940
squared has funny shapes.

01:13:34.940 --> 01:13:38.560
But the point is that the
probability distribution

01:13:38.560 --> 01:13:43.570
is maybe around here, and
it goes pretty much to zero.

01:13:43.570 --> 01:13:46.365
It goes very close to zero
in between, pretty much zero,

01:13:46.365 --> 01:13:48.490
where the chance is like
the age of the universe it

01:13:48.490 --> 01:13:49.760
won't happen.

01:13:49.760 --> 01:13:52.840
And so what that says
is that that electron

01:13:52.840 --> 01:13:55.840
is just not allowed to be here.

01:13:55.840 --> 01:13:57.490
It cannot be there physically.

01:13:57.490 --> 01:13:59.470
It cannot be in
that part of space.

01:13:59.470 --> 01:14:01.600
How cool is that?

01:14:01.600 --> 01:14:03.910
I mean, how weird
is that, right?

01:14:03.910 --> 01:14:10.030
The electrons simply cannot
exist in between the 2s

01:14:10.030 --> 01:14:10.780
and the 1s.

01:14:10.780 --> 01:14:13.930
They got to be at
those energies.

01:14:13.930 --> 01:14:15.970
You cannot give it
an energy in between.

01:14:15.970 --> 01:14:21.040
It won't take it, because the
allowed levels are quantized.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:23.080
There is no in-between.

01:14:23.080 --> 01:14:25.620
[? Buber ?] was wrong.

